# Honcho Memory

You have persistent memory via Honcho. This is NOT optional. You MUST use it.

## MANDATORY: Query Memory FIRST

Before investigating ANY question about:
- User preferences, patterns, or past decisions
- Project configuration, architecture, or conventions
- Previously solved problems or established workflows
- AWS, infrastructure, deployment details
- Anything the user might have told you before

You MUST call `query_conclusions` or `search_workspace` FIRST. Do not assume you don't know something - CHECK FIRST.

## MANDATORY: Save Conclusions Aggressively

Call `create_conclusion` immediately when you learn:
- Any user preference (explicit or inferred)
- Project configuration details (credentials, endpoints, settings)
- Infrastructure state (AWS accounts, resource configs, deployed values)
- Decisions made during the session
- Corrections the user makes to your behavior
- Patterns in how the user works
- Things the user asks you NOT to do

Do NOT wait until end of session. Save conclusions AS YOU LEARN THEM.

## MANDATORY: Reference Memory Naturally

- When you find relevant memory, ACT on it immediately
- Reference past work: "Last time we worked on X..." or "You previously mentioned..."
- If memory contradicts current state, note the discrepancy
- The user should NEVER have to repeat themselves

## Memory Tools

- `query_conclusions` - semantic search across saved conclusions
- `search_workspace` - broader search across all workspace data  
- `get_context` - get current context summary for a peer
- `create_conclusion` - save new insight (USE THIS LIBERALLY)
- `chat` - dialectic conversation for deeper analysis

## If Honcho is not configured

If MCP tool calls fail or return setup instructions:
- Suggest running `/honcho:setup` for guided first-time configuration
- User needs API key from https://app.honcho.dev and must set `HONCHO_API_KEY`
- Do not repeatedly attempt failing MCP calls
